def perc_on_bar(feature):
    """
    plot
    feature: categorical feature
    the function won't work if a column is passed in the hue parameter
    """
    # Creating a countplot for the feature
    sns.set(rc={"figure.figsize": (25, 5)})
    ax = sns.countplot(x=feature, data=labels)

    total = len(feature)  # length of the column
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = "{:.1f}%".format(
            100 * p.get_height() / total
        )  # percentage of each class of the category
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.1  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()  # hieght of the plot
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size=14)  # annotate the percantage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Display images¶

  • find all unique classes and then find the index of the first occurence of each class, save as a tuple containing the unique label and it's index of first occurence
  • then plot the images using the array of tuples found in previous step
In [19]:
unique_classes = labels['Label'].unique()
indexes_found = []
for val in unique_classes:
  idx = labels['Label'].eq(val).idxmax()
  pair = (val, idx)
  indexes_found.append(pair)
indexes_found

In [23]:
def display_images(img_source):
  fig = plt.figure(figsize=(16, 8))
  fig.set_size_inches(16, 16)
  for i in range(0, len(indexes_found)):
    ax = plt.subplot(4, 4, i + 1)
    ax.axis('Off')
    plt.title(indexes_found[i][0])
    plt.imshow(img_source[indexes_found[i][1]])
  plt.show()

display_images(images)

Observations

  • The dataset contains 4750 RGB images of size 128x128 pixels
  • There are 4750 labels of 12 unique categories

Apply Gaussian Blur¶

In [21]:
from skimage.filters import gaussian
blurred_images = [];
for img in normalized_images:
  blurred_images.append(gaussian(img, sigma=1))
blurred = np.array(blurred_images)
blurred.shape
Out[21]:
(4750, 128, 128, 3)
In [24]:
display_images(blurred)

Observations

  • As you can see, we successfully blurred the images
  • We could have also defined a two-dimensional gaussian filter and convolved it over each channel and then stacked them up, but there is a library to do all that

Build the model¶

In [30]:
cnn_model = Sequential()
cnn_model.add(Conv2D(16, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(128, 128, 3)))
cnn_model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
cnn_model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu'))
cnn_model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
cnn_model.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'))
cnn_model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
cnn_model.add(Flatten())
cnn_model.add(Dense(512, activation='relu'))
cnn_model.add(Dense(12, activation='softmax'))

cnn_model.compile(loss="categorical_crossentropy", optimizer="Adam", metrics = ['accuracy'])

Another model with different architecture¶

Note: This model was provided to us during mentoring session. The difference here is that this model has one more Convolution layer, also there are added Dropout layers after each convolution and pooling.

In [96]:
es = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', verbose=1, patience=20)
mc = ModelCheckpoint('best_model.h5', monitor='val_accuracy', mode='max', verbose=1, save_best_only=True)
model = Sequential()

model.add(Conv2D(filters = 16, kernel_size = (5,5),padding = 'Same', 
                 activation ='relu', input_shape = (128,128,3)))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))
#
model.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3,3),padding = 'Same', 
                 activation ='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2), strides=(2,2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.25))
#
model.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3,3),padding = 'Same', 
                 activation ='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2), strides=(2,2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))
#
model.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (2,2),padding = 'Same', 
                 activation ='relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2), strides=(2,2)))
model.add(Dropout(0.3))

# 
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(1024, activation = "relu"))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(12, activation = "softmax"))
optimizer = Adam(lr=0.001, beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999)
model.compile(optimizer = optimizer , loss = "categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
epochs = 200  
batch_size = 64



es = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', mode='min', verbose=1, patience=5)
mc = ModelCheckpoint('best_model.h5', monitor='val_accuracy', mode='max', verbose=1, save_best_only=True)

history=model.fit(X_train, 
          y_train,  #It expects integers because of the sparse_categorical_crossentropy loss function
          epochs=50,#number of iterations over the entire dataset to train on
          batch_size=128,callbacks=[es, mc],use_multiprocessing=True, validation_data=(X_val, y_val), verbose = 1)#number of samples per gradient update for training

Observations

  • I don't really know how to visualize this data, but we can see that the model correctly predicts 4 out of 5 images, which, to me, is impressive
  • My model confused Cleavers with small-flowered cranesbill, which may be due to blurring, or some other noise

Conclusion¶

  • I trained two models in order to complete this project. The first one had very low scores. The second model, for which I've added dropout layers after each convolution and pooling layer and also a dropout between the dense layers, did significantly better. But still things can probably be improved by manipulating the hyperparameters
  • For me, playing around with the number of epochs and batches made a significant impact. When I used 10 epochs for training, my model wouldn't even be able to reach 15% accuracy. That is why I decreased batch size from 256 to 128 and increased the number of epochs to 50.
  • I still feel that the model performance can be improved by exprerimenting with the hyperparameters. I also keep wondering what would happen if I hadn't applied Gaussian blurring?
  • Also, the labels dataset was not balanced. I could have augmented some images and see where that would take me. (I'm sure I could gain a couple of score metrics by that)
